    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:342e9d2b-e112-4b9d-82b8-c17567acff5c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 71-year-old retired schoolteacher who lives alone in a quiet suburban neighborhood after her husband passed away six years ago. She is a slight but spirited woman with silver-streaked hair worn in a neat bun, though friends and former colleagues have noticed she appears visibly thinner and more fatigued than she did even a year ago. She stands at 5'4\" and has lost approximately 12 pounds over the past four months, a change she initially attributed to \"eating less now that I cook for one.\" She spent 35 years in a classroom, during which time she smoked one pack of cigarettes a day; she quit at age 58 following a minor cardiac scare but accumulated a 37 pack-year smoking history.\n\n{patientName} presented to her primary care physician complaining of a persistent, worsening cough that she had dismissed as post-nasal drip for several months. More recently, she developed episodes of blood-streaked sputum (hemoptysis), progressive dyspnea on exertion — she can no longer walk up her front porch steps without stopping — and a dull, aching right-sided chest pain that she rates 4/10 at rest and 7/10 when she coughs. She also reports profound fatigue, intermittent low-grade fevers, and night sweats that have disrupted her sleep for the past six weeks.\n\nOutside of her medical concerns, {patientName} is an avid watercolor painter and volunteers at the local library reading program twice a week, activities she now struggles to keep up with due to breathlessness and fatigue. She has two adult children and four grandchildren who live nearby and are closely involved in her care. She is a non-drinker and adheres to a Mediterranean-style diet. She relies on Medicare and a supplemental insurance plan. A CT scan of the chest confirmed a 4.2 cm spiculated mass in the right lower lobe with ipsilateral mediastinal lymphadenopathy, raising strong suspicion for primary lung malignancy.\n\nBiopsy confirmed a diagnosis of non-small cell lung carcinoma (adenocarcinoma histology), staged as IIIA. Molecular profiling showed no actionable EGFR, ALK, or ROS1 mutations, but PD-L1 expression was elevated (TPS 65%), making her a candidate for immunotherapy combined with platinum-based chemotherapy. Her oncology team has initiated a treatment plan accordingly and she is currently receiving her second cycle of therapy."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
